<DOC><DOCNO> AP881213-0208 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 2131EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     12-13 0281</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru-Rebels,0290</SECOND><HEAD>Six Die in Guerrilla Attacks Across Peru</HEAD><DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Marxist rebels looted government buildings andbattled police at a river port during a jungle raid that left threepeople dead, authorities said Tuesday.   In the Andes Mountains, Maoist guerrillas killed an army officer,a mayor, and a policeman in three separate incidents, police alsosaid.   Two guerrillas of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, apro-Cuban group, and a villager were killed Sunday when theinsurgents clashed with police defending Puerto Inca. The town is onthe bank of the Pachitea River 135 miles northeast of Lima.   About 50 rebels ransacked and looted a government developmentoffice and two state banks before they were driven off, police said.   The Tupac Amaru group began attacks, mainly in Lima and otherurban centers, in 1984.   In the Andes, a larger Maoist guerrilla group known as theShining Path executed an army captain, police said. He was incivilian dress, but the rebels checked his identification anddragged him from an interstate bus Monday near Concepcion, 120 mileseast of Lima, authorities said.   They said other Shining Path insurgents on Monday executed MayorAlfredo Chamorro in the village of Pallanchacra near Concepcion.   Also Monday, police and rebels from the group were reported toclash at a mountain pass near Cuzco, 355 miles southeast of Lima. Apoliceman was killed and five Shining Path guerrillas were wounded,police said.   The Shining Path has been fighting since 1980 to topple Peru'selected government. It is not believed to maintain ties with theTupac Amaru group.   The government says more than 12,000 people have died in violencestemming from the Shining Path insurgency.</TEXT></DOC>